  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">The only beneficial right that Ringwalt<BR ALIGN='left'/>relinquished under the trust agreement<BR ALIGN='left'/>was the right to receive trust receipts<BR ALIGN='left'/>allocable to income. Ringwalt had<BR ALIGN='left'/>numerous powers of administration over<BR ALIGN='left'/>the trust. The trust assets were subject<BR ALIGN='left'/>to execution by Ringwalt&#x27;s creditors.<BR ALIGN='left'/>Ringwalt also retained a reversionary<BR ALIGN='left'/>interest in the corpus of the trust to<BR ALIGN='left'/>insure that he would be entitled to<BR ALIGN='left'/>total control after ten years.\n\nMost<BR ALIGN='left'/>significantly, examination of the<BR ALIGN='left'/>declaration of trust reveals that<BR ALIGN='left'/>Ringwalt as trustee possessed extensive<BR ALIGN='left'/>power to allocate trust receipts between<BR ALIGN='left'/>principal and income.</TD></TR>
